Key Insights & Analysis

  • Health Impact: Average of 2.3 estimated respiratory cases per day
  • Pollution Levels: PM2.5 average of 71.2 µg/m³ (exceeds WHO guidelines)
  • Primary Correlate: CO (mg/m3) shows strongest correlation (r = 0.097)
  • Data Quality: 100.0% complete

Key Characteristics

  • Legacy industrial pollution (SAIL steel plant 70+ years). Extreme seasonal health variation (strongest analyzed)
  • Healthcare capacity crisis (severe understaffing). Industrial worker health paradox (jobs but health crisis)
  • Limited environmental monitoring (no weather/advanced parameters)
  • Rourkela demonstrates the long-term health consequences of legacy industrial pollution with inadequate healthcare infrastructure

    *Synthetic Data Considerations

    • Population: ~677,000 (metro 2025), ~396,000 (city); literacy 86.98%; 54% male, 46% female; sex ratio 888/1000; 32% in Odisha state live below poverty line
    • Respiratory Disease: Overall respiratory morbidity 183.31 per 1000 person-year; URTI most common (76.79 per 1000); follows national patterns—Asthma ~30%, COPD ~15-16%; higher rates likely due to steel plant industrial pollution
    • Healthcare: Rourkela Government Hospital severely understaffed (58 doctors for 138 posts); new Apollo-SAIL 290-bed multi-specialty hospital launched; railway hospital faces infrastructure gaps
    • Seasonal Patterns: Strong winter peaks—respiratory morbidity increases from 53.11 (summer) to 75.5 per 1000 (winter); positive correlation with PM2.5 (r=0.94)
    • Socioeconomic: Major steel manufacturing hub (SAIL plant since 1954); 36.6% slum population (1.14 lakh people); urban density driven by industrial activity; 71,368 households total
